Minimum KL →\rightarrow→ Maximum entropy

In the previous chapter, we saw what happens when we minimize qqq in the KL divergence D(p,q)D(p, q)D(p,q). We used this to find the best model of data ppp.

In this chapter, we will ponder the second question - what happens if we minimize ppp in D(p,q)D(p, q)D(p,q)? This way, we will build the so-called maximum entropy principle that guides us whenever we want to choose a good model distribuiton.

💡If there is one thing you remember from this chapter...

Max-entropy principle constructs the most generic distributions satifying some constraints. Most useful distributions are max-entropy for some parameter.

Conditioning on steroids

Suppose I want to determine a probability distribution modelling the random variable XXX of how long it takes me to eat lunch. My initial (and very crude) model of XXX might be a uniform distribution qqq between and minutes.

Starting with this model, I can try to get some new information and condition on it to get a better model ppp.

For example, let's say that after eating many lunches, I observe that I always finish after at most 30 minutes. I can turn this to a new information that X≤30X \le 30X≤30. I can condition on this information and get a better model:

Let's try again. I eat many more lunches, but this time I keep recording the average time it takes me to eat lunch. Say, it turns out to be 15 minutes. How do I change qqq to reflect this new information? The probability theory gives a clear answer.

We simply can't do this. In probability theory, we can condition on events like X≤30X \le 30X≤30, i.e., facts that are true for some values that XXX can attend, but not others. But now we would like to condition on E[X]=15E[X] = 15E[X]=15 which is not an event, just a fact that's true for some distributions over XXX, but not others.

The fun part is that we can use KL divergence to 'condition' on E[X]=15E[X] = 15E[X]=15. It turns out that the most reasonable way to account for the new information is to choose as the model minimizing KL divergence to qqq. That is, for the set PPP of distributions ppp with Ep[X]=15E_p[X] = 15Ep​[X]=15, choose

In the example, happens to look like exponential distribution:

This is sometimes called the minimum relative entropy principle. Why does this make sense? Intuitively, I want to find a distribution that would serve as the new best guess for what the truth is, while the old model distribution remains as good a model of ppp as possible. This is what we achieve by minimizing KL divergence D(p,q)D(p, q)D(p,q).

Admittedly, this intuition may feel a bit shaky, as we typically prefer ppp to represent the "true" distribution when using KL divergence, whereas here it's simply a new, improved, model. There's a more technical argument called Wallis derivation that explains why we can derive minimum relative entropy as "conditioning on steroids" from the first principles.

The maximum entropy principle

Let's delve deeper into the minimum relative entropy principle. A conceptual issue with it is that it only allows us to refine an existing model qqq into a better model ppp. But how did we choose the initial model qqq in the first place? It feels a bit like a chicken-and-egg dilemma.

Fortunately, there's usually a very natural choice for the simplest possible model qqq: the uniform distribution. This is the unique most 'even' distribution that assigns the same probability to every possible outcome. There's also a fancy name for using the uniform distribution as the safe-haven model in the absence of any relevant evidence: the principle of indifference.

It would be highly interesting to understand what happens when we combine both principles together. That is, say that we start with the uniform distribution (say it's uniform over the set {1,…,k}\{1, \dots, k\}{1,…,k}). What happens if we find a better model by minimizing KL divergence? Let's write it out:

We've just derived what's known as the maximum entropy principle: given a set PPP of distributions to choose from, we should opt for the p∈Pp\in Pp∈P that maximizes the entropy H(p)H(p)H(p).

General form of maximum entropy distributions

Let's now dive a bit deeper into maximum entropy. We'll try to understand what maximum entropy distributions actually look like. For example, we will see soon how does the maximum entropy distribution with E[X]=15E[X] = 15E[X]=15 looks like.

Here's what I want you to focus on, though. Let's not worry about concrete numbers like 15 too much. To get the most out of the max-entropy principle, we have to think about the questions a bit more abstractly, more like: _If I fix the value of E[X]E[X]E[X], what shape will the max-entropy distribution have?

For such a broad question, the answer turns out to be surprisingly straightforward! Before telling you the general answer, let's see a couple of examples.

If we consider distributions with a fixed expectation E[X]=μE[X] = \muE[X]=μ (and the domain is non-negative real numbers), the maximum entropy distribution is the exponential distribution. Why?

Let's build some intuition for this. Remember from the previous chapter that the max-entropy principle is essentially about finding a distribution that is as close to uniform as possible, in the sense of minimizing KL divergence.

So, in what way are max-entropy distributions "close" to being uniform? Let's use the exponential distribution p(x)∝e−xp(x) \propto e^{-x}p(x)∝e−x as an example. Say I independently sample two numbers from it, x1x_1x1​ and x2x_2x2​. Here's a little riddle: Is it more probable that I sample x1=10,x2=20x_1 = 10, x_2 = 20x1​=10,x2​=20 or that I sample x1′=15,x2′=15x_1' = 15, x_2' = 15x1′​=15,x2′​=15?

The answer is that both options have the same probability density. That's because p(x1)⋅p(x2)=e−x1−x2p(x_1)\cdot p(x_2) = e^{-x_1 - x_2}p(x1​)⋅p(x2​)=e−x1​−x2​. In our riddle, x1+x2=x1′+x2′x_1 + x_2 = x_1' + x_2'x1​+x2​=x1′​+x2′​, so both possibilities have a density proportional to e−30e^{-30}e−30.

You can imagine this as a generalization of the widget above. There's a super complicated space of all possible outcomes I can get by sampling nnn times from my distribution. The max-entropy property says that if I draw a "contour" through outcomes that share the same empirical averages of the functions f1,…,fmf_1, \dots, f_mf1​,…,fm​, the conditional distribution is uniform on this contour.

So, what's the takeaway? When you sample from max-entropy distributions, the experience is actually quite similar to sampling from a uniform distribution - the distribution over outcomes is uniform once you condition on the value of relevant properties! 2

Catalogue of examples

Let's go through the list of maximum-entropy distributions you might have encountered. In fact, most distributions used in practice are maximum entropy distributions for some specific choice of functions f1,…fmf_1, \dots f_mf1​,…fm​.

So, when you come across a distribution, the right question isn't really "Is this a max entropy distribution?" It's more like, "For what parameters is this a max entropy distribution?" For example, you can forget the exact formula for the Gaussian distribution—it's enough to remember that using it implies you believe the mean and variance are the most important parameters to consider.

Let's go through the examples with this in mind. Please, do skip whatever doesn't ring a bell, the list is long.

Let's start with what happens if we don't have any constraints.
